{"word":"αἴθω","slug":"αἴθω","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>αἴθω</b></el> <p/><div class='li750'><b>1. </b><i>to light up, kindle</i>, <b><a href='S:Herodotus'>Hdt.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Tragic, in Tragic Greek'>Trag.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>2. </b><a href='S:intransitive'>intr.</a> <i>to burn</i> or <i>blaze</i>, <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b>:—in this sense the <a href='S:passive signification'><a href='S:Passive Voice'>Pass.</a></a> <el>αἴθομαι</el> is used by <b><a href='S:Homer'>Hom.</a></b> in <a href='S:participle'>part.</a>, <el>πυρὸς μένος αἰθομένοιο</el> <b><a href='S:Iliad'>Il.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Odyssey'>Od.</a></b>, <a href='S:et cetera'>etc.</a>; so <a href='S:metaphorically'>metaph.</a>, <el>ἔρωτι αἴθεσθαι</el> <b><a href='S:Xenophon'>Xen.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}